segments.text: We had begun on this campus to develop a more than casual interaction with the Corvette Corporation.
They were routinely here trying to sell us a big computer.
And through the flow of many, many pulled out people through the Martin family in Texas, they have learned about India.
They were intrigued.
Word had gotten back to the CDC.
So I was invited to come up and meet Bill Morris, the author who described the Invit program, and visit their, what they call their BDC, Spitz Technologies.
That meeting had been set up, and
About the time Bart Henson came here as chancellor, I told him that I was the one that he got very interested in.
At any rate, he went with me.
And so he and I went out for him to see Bill Norris in Warfare and some of the top officers in Central Valley.
And I described the Invincible to him.
And all this related to our own
the evolving research part, which I had co-chaired, or vice-chaired, the committee on the research part with Chancellor Hubert, who was then the chairman.
But anyway, the MCC document was out, or coming out, and I got an advance copy of the announcement.
because of having established that relationship with the man and the company that was the creator of the idea.
We had agreed to host here on this campus the, probably the fourth, third or fourth or fifth, I forget the number,
by any conference on university, industry, government, microwave products.
It was a conference that the IEEE had initiated, one part of the IEEE had initiated, oh, six or eight, maybe now ten years ago.
And I'd been involved in that.
Indeed, I'd structured the first one of them.
At the time, I was on the administrative committee of the
the division of the IEEE that got us started.
And we just turned out going to have it at Texas A&M.
I guess that was last year, the year before last, whatever the year was that MCC was to come.
Well, I'd ask Bill Norris, because I knew he was a pivotal player in the evolution of MCC.
commit to having whoever was going to be president of MCC be the keynote speaker for our conference, our University of the Ministry of Government Michael O'Connor Symposium here.
And he said he would.
So before Bob Inman ever became president of MCC, he was committed unknowingly to come here to be the keynote speaker at our conference.
Well, the MCC thing moved.
They did all of their interviews.
Mark White went to the Hyatt Hotel in Chicago repair.
That was in March of 1983.
Don Walker and Art Hanson met as the chancellors of the UT A&M system.
I knew well of the need, thought for a while I was going to have to go because Art Hanson had a conflict.
He was able to work that conflict out and go on.
I remember all this weather well because I was hitting, supposedly, with my family on a spring break trip to Utah.
I was asked on the day of the meeting to sit by the phone in the condo in case there were any technical questions that came up.
I remember well sitting in the... You still have to go to Utah.
Oh, yeah, but one day I missed the day of the meeting.
I sat by the fire and watched the snow fall and waited to see if the phone rang in case there was any need.
So that happened in March of 1983.
Through that sequence of interviews, the MCC thing then narrowed down to four cities, one of which was Austin.
The governor called the meeting one Sunday evening, probably.
I look back at my calendar and get the date.
But here in sometime last year, before MCC made their forced march, as Inman put it, through the four cities, which were, what, San Diego, Atlanta, Raleigh, Durham, North Carolina, and Austin, Texas.
He picked by some mechanism, I'm not sure what, about 20 people to come over one Sunday evening to talk about the strategy of how we should get ready to compete.
Some of the obvious reasons
players that were there, at least for me.
Henry Cisneros, whose presentation in Chicago had been better than anybody's, so stated by MCC.
But they couldn't go to San Antonio because there wasn't a major university there that they could draw.
And that was the only reason.
Otherwise, San Antonio would have had it.
I was there in R. Hanson's behalf.
He had a conflict that he could not get out of, and so he asked me to go and represent the A&M system.
Don Walker was there representing the UT system.
He and I met, Walker and I met in his office about an hour beforehand.
to explore how UT and A&M would cooperate in this venture, which was probably the first meeting of its kind in history.
And an interesting meeting, and I've grown to be quite fond of Don Walker for no other reason than just based on that opportunity to begin to talk about how we'd work together.
We really just said, you know,
Gee, we'll just go in and tell them, UT and A&M are going to back this deal, whatever's required, and see how it goes.
And I thought I might basically follow his lead, since it was in Austin.
It was the city, not College Station.
We'll now tie together the other piece of the story for me.
Because as we met, we were only about three weeks away.
I don't know, a short time away from this conference here in A&M.
The brochures were printed, the speakers were there, and the announcement was Bobby Inman, president of MCC, keynote speaker.
And I took several of those with me that night to distribute among the people that were there.
Tease's role in attracting MCC became rather obvious to the people sitting in that room that night.
None of them had any idea, first of all, that the conference was there.
Secondly, that arrangements had already been made for the president of MCC, who had only been on board
a very short period of time, was the keynote speaker.
I've never told them how that was arranged, by the way.
Not for any reason other than it's just never been the opportunity to tell them.
But I always will remember the impact that had that evening when I passed out those brochures in the conference.
As it turned out, on the personal side of the thing, part of the, that was personally satisfying, and that's why, and that's obvious that that would be.
I was, at that time, again, on my way to Saudi Arabia.

I had been asked by the University of Petroleum and Minerals and by Dr. Pickering, who was the previous director of the Department of Culture, who had spent two years building a research institute, not December, at the University of Petroleum and Minerals in Dairon.
I had been asked to join Dr. Pickering in spending two weeks there reviewing the research program of this research institute and was on my way the next week.
At the same time frame the advanced scout team of MCC was to come to Texas and we were planning that evening what and who they should see.
already rescheduled this trip to Saudi Arabia once, maybe twice, I'm not sure.

And I said to the governor that evening, I said, well, you know, if we decide that I personally need to be present for that visit, then clearly, obviously, the project has to go home, rescheduled, or just canceled.
Perot, Ross Perot, said, well, look, couldn't you just go by and meet Bobby?
I said, I still haven't met him.
He said, could you swing by Washington on your way to study?
And meet him.
Just leave a day early.
Because I was flying out of New York anyway.
I said, yes, I can meet him.
I would not be concerned about having to be there unless we just felt like an administrative or political business or whatever.
Ross Perot's request or suggestion or demand or whatever Ross does, that I go on the way to Saudi and meet him.
So I didn't.
So I just left here a day early, flew into D.C.
met with Perot, I mean, met with him over in Arlington, Virginia for, well, less than a half an hour.
And I asked him if he had any questions he wanted to ask about Texas and why NCC was going to come.
And he grinned and said, no, not really.
He, uh,
He had his scout team out.
He wasn't playing it as he should have.
He said, is there anything that you want to tell me?
And I said, well, Texas is where you need to be.
And if you should make the mistake of not locating physically in Texas, you're still going to find yourself deep in Texas.
Because we've got, in our Institute for Solid State Electronics, the talent
and the research capability that you're going to have to access sooner or later.
And he said, OK. And then I gave him a copy of the conference brochure where he was going to speak.
He didn't know that already.
Yeah, he didn't know that already.
He said, yes, I have that on my calendar.
And I said, well, I thought you might like to have a copy of this.
It's probably in the mail to you right now, but I left him with a couple more and thanked him for accepting so graciously to do it.
And I told him we were excited about him coming down.
We had a nice, brief, but to the point visit.
He left to go testify to some Senate hearing committee, and I left to go to Saudi Arabia.
I extended to him at the time, probably when he came we'd have a little dinner for him.
We got together and I'd introduce him to some of these key players in this microelectronics business.
And then he would meet many of them at the conference from all over the country.
If he came in the night before the conference that we hosted in the house and invited some key researchers, the doers, the brains, the hat dogs, so that he could meet them in Portland, which I did.
But I believe that conference actually occurred after the decision was made for them to come to Texas.
Because they moved on that decision very quickly.
But we hosted in the Batch Scout team a number of MCC people here on campus.
They visited our solid state institute.

Our larger MicroLocunt program, which has now grown in the EE division of TEAS to be run as a substitute interaction, we now have had, as you're probably aware, a design program linked with Texas Instruments that's now four years old.
All of that was up and running.
Again, we weren't talking about what we were getting ready to do.
We were showing examples of product designs that have been reduced to practice.
the students that were coming out the door.
I think it played a measurable role in the university.
And so, the governor thought something.
I read the article in the paper where he cited the groups that he's been close to and just gave the credit to the team, and he didn't give it to anyone.
Well, I got a lot of calls from Houston alumni when that article hit about, hey, you can't let them get away with this, because otherwise it will become history.
So it was, I thought, very appropriate what the governor had to say.
Was that said at the end, after you contacted him, or was this something that... You wouldn't think I wrote what you got, I have to say.
It sounded like you'd gotten on the phone and said, hey, you know.
As a matter of fact, we did.
Of course, he wouldn't have put it out again.
No way.
Now, he had to say it.
Well, as I said, UT and Texas A&M cooperating on something.
I think this was the big spark.
It was the first, and we knocked it out of the park.
Absolutely.
You can't quarrel with the success of what impression it made on MCC as an industry.
And that these two major university systems were prepared to work together to get them to company.
Otherwise it would have been bloody.
As is normal.
How do you administratively go about doing away with a particular area of research that has become frivolous?
Well, every idea, every product, every person has a life, a predictable life.
Some live longer than others.
But the signs that it's over here,
are usually pretty obvious.
If we have a research division whose time has come to be terminated, the first sign of that is that nobody wants to support the research division.
Another sign of it is that
Even if resources are available, that is what I call seed dollars or T's, typically the kind of money you put in when you're creating to do with the seed if it makes sense.
You measure it pretty much the same way you do in the beginning.
You've got an idea of an area that you feel
is important and should go, so you put some money in.
And you support that concept by bringing in the right people, by building the right facilities, by buying the right equipment.
And you nurture them.
And then you see if they grow and they're healthy.
And if they do, they bloom into something meaningful.
And that's measured by their peers, not only at their own institution, but throughout the world.
by how well their work is received in their own profession, their professional societies and professional journals.
And it's measured by their ability to compete with their peers.
And they're all in that entity.
You're sticking with your question.
How do you decide when it's time for an entity or a division or an area to terminate?
Well, the analogy I'm trying to draw is the same way, you know, if a baby's born and you nourish it, you coddle it, and it dies, something's wrong with it.
It didn't grow into a healthy being.

that could defend itself, that could take care of itself, that could get kicked out of the nest, could go to college by itself, could learn on its own, could wash its own clothes, could compete with his peers for a valedictorian spot or the best job or position or what he wanted to do.
If you'll let me personify a little bit, the entity itself functions the same way.

If you put $50,000 into a microelectronics idea in 1968 and it isn't ready to play on the team at the national level of bringing MCC to Texas, we probably would have never been there in the first place.
I'd say that one worked.
But we put money into ideas before that didn't catch.
urban affairs.

We moved it, transferred it, you know, took it off the symbol act, put it on goat's milk, took it off the goat's milk, put it on the, you know, tried it in this environment, in that environment, gee, it looked like it was doing good for a while, and oops, you know, went pale again.
We're running an experiment right now, a dramatic experiment, and that's in me.
No idea how that's going to work.
We're nurturing it, feeding it, coddling it, exposing it to this, that, and the other.
But it's got to grow up and stand on its own feet.
Well, if an entity that's been healthy, been working, been doing those things that
are clear and obvious signs of health, of being meaningful and contributing to it.
If it begins to get sick by whatever symptoms you use to measure, and you use all of those, then you analyze if administratively, has the administration gotten in the way?
Kind of come back to your other question.
Have you done something stupid?
that's caused a problem, or has the technology matured that it represented to a point that the need for further research and development is just no longer there?
That's recently happened in the remote cities.
You redefined that.
That's right.
But see, NASA, when John Rouse took over the remote sensing, remote sensing as a technology application in space, defining what it would do, how it would do it, was at its infancy.
Now, routine.
Launch them, let them read.
We lost the NASA support.
Not because we weren't any good anymore, but because they had what they needed.
And so we've turned a corner.
That's natural.
It's change.
But you have to, the greatest mistake the administration has made, I think, is not to be willing to do it.
Not to want to do it.
Not to treat it as progress, as natural.
But want the status quo, want to preserve what you know how to do.
It's traumatic.
It's traumatic on people's lives.
It's traumatic, you know, I've got to reprint a new brochure and take the damn thing out of there.
There are a lot of traumatic things about making change.
So if you're not willing to deal with that or don't want to deal with that or don't want to be bothered with that, that's when I think the administrative structure gets in the way.
Not when you go in and you say to the head of one of those divisions,
It's not performing well.
Hey, your division's not performing very well.
What's wrong?
Do you need some help?
Are we in the way?
Is it the administration's fault?
Or have you got a problem with what you're doing and the need for it?
Do you need to reassess where you're going and how you're going to get there?
I think the administration's responsibility, I feel my responsibility as a director is just to answer the questions.

And if I find somebody that doesn't want to answer them, demand that they be answered and come down hard enough with whatever I've got to come down with to be sure that we, together, then come to an agreement and an understanding of what we're doing and what it's costing to do and is it worth the cost.
Now, TEAS tries to make all the research divisions pay.
Besides seed money?
Yeah, typically, indeed this year, I just got this letter back yesterday from the Governor's Budget Office and the Legislative Budget Office approving the new format.
Which I think makes a lot of sense and makes it easier to explain it to the average layman, which is what you deal with in the political process.
Why is TEAS existing and why do the taxpayers
Why should the taxpayer pay?
Why should we be taxed off?
Essentially, I'm trying to break it down in an evolutionary cycle in three stages.
And that's the startup program.
And Ben is a good example.
And in a startup program, that program, we have to be, we ETs, we the taxpayers, prepared to pay 100% of the cost.

And what I want to be able to do is to say clearly to the legislature, that is, that entity that represents the clerk checking groceries out there, throwing some of her cash or his cash into the coffers, that here's why I believe this program makes sense.
is going to help our society as a whole in Texas by doing this.
And we need to be prepared collectively to put our money into debt servicing.
And that's a startup program.
Depending upon the complexity of that program, the market it serves, its objectives, on the average, I would say, a startup program would evolve

a developing in about three years at which point if it's catching on if it's really working or beginning to work like we felt it would it will be returning it will be earning dollar for dollar and then
when it matures or becomes established, it will bring in to the state $4 for every $1 we pay for an annual basis.
That is, you'll get a 400% per annum return.
That's on the average.
Hence, to answer your question,
On the average, TEAS sets as a target for an established, mature, meaningful program that it should generate 80% of its budget.
We do have programs that do it.
Sure.
And I have programs that
For every dollar we put in, it ran 30 times.
But it's more of a service to the system.
That's right.
We don't even treat those divisions of kids like that, because a service division is created for that purpose.
And if a service division can break even, you deal with it.
And the service divisions include the DPC and the Nuclear Science Center?
DPC, Nuclear Science Center, and the Injury Counseling.
That's really a high-precision model.
The DPC, of course, is no longer quarantined.
We did it September.
We moved it to the university.
There's a nuclear science center still.
The nuclear science center functions under the division, the service division of the DPC.

Although at the request of the head of the Nuclear Engineering Division two years ago, maybe three, the desire to integrate the Nuclear Science Center more into the research program of the Nuclear Engineering Division, we have the Nuclear Science Center reporting to this office through the Nuclear Engineering Division.
That's right.
Well, it's a controlling your own destiny thing.
It's not a service center that they don't feel like they have as much control over.
And in my mind, it makes sense.

But then that puts a lot of pressure on the nuclear engineer to be sure that the nuclear reactor does indeed do the research that it would like to have it for and that it participates more in as a research program than a service center.
and generates the meaningful, valuable results to the citizens of this state to justify the cause they're operating in.
You said the data processing center transferred in September.
Is that this year or next year?
Does it come in September?
No, it was patched up in September.
Besides the dissemination of information and PR that Benson and others told you to prosecute in Canada, are there any other clues they gave to you as to what areas they felt please them to do that?
Well, that was the key hurdle from Fred Benson.
Others, if you read our Target 2000 study, which kind of followed the Texas study, the citizens of this state were asked to come in and review the purpose, goals, and objectives of the NU system.
and taking advantage of the opportunities they have to serve the needs of Texas.
To get a greater presence in the metropolitan area would be one of the challenges and objectives set forth for Texas.
Or to create a presence in
the area where the people are to make it easier to access the capabilities.
That's one of the directives that's come forward.
One of the ones I sent for this agency that I felt strongly about coming into this office and still do is the International.
I believe that, particularly with our neighbors, Mexico and Canada, but not limited to Canada.
The world isn't what it used to be.
It's a small place.
Is this something you held before Vanderbilt came out as a global university?
Oh, sure.
That's where I was going to China in 1979, Russia in 1977, Saudi Arabia last year.
So you were very connected to the sky.
He coincided rather well.
He was having my teeth.
And we worked pretty hard at that.
We don't have any MCC examples.
We have some satisfying experiences, but nothing that needs to happen.
When Tease first started, he had a large education role in the Education Act.
How has that changed since you've been here, or has it changed?
I think it's increased.
The role Tease plays
by encouraging and supporting the church and its ability to do that.
And probably with my willingness, one of the, what you would call radical movements in the current, since I've been the director and I'm the vice-director, as they say,
is that TEAS has had new interdisciplinary divisions open up, interacting with the College of Business, Global Arms, GSN, and Education.
First of all, it scared the College of Engineering to death, because they saw, or thought they saw, resources going out.
Now this is all perception.
But very accurate perception.
Oh, I guess all this is actually documented.
for a lot of very real and good reasons.
From an administrative and financial standpoint, because of state laws, state funding, etc.
But it was a difficult decision for the university to make.
And I was not prepared to make that decision unilaterally.
In all of those decisions, the deans of those colleges came to me with a request to create a tax revision.
I asked for proposals of why they thought it made sense, other than we might have some resources in the faculty, and discussed at length with them.
how we would do, what role the technology and engineering represents would play in the research and in the disciplines that they represent.
And why they felt this integration, this interdisciplinary approach, would be valuable.
I had my own opinions from day one, which were pro that approach that caused me to listen to them.
But once I got all of that in front of them, and all of this didn't happen at once, it came in stages.
The first one we moved to was the College of Business, and it would have been started because of income.
One of the small movements of our business.
But at that time, the College of Business didn't have no insurance.
Zero.
That Texas A&M University never had no service.
We created a division of business and technology three years ago now.
That's different from the industrial development division that was part of the strategic division.
Yeah, that's that urban affairs thing I told you about.
I moved that deal around, you know, finally into the business technology division.
It's been absorbed in that.
That kind of research, and that's the work long.
Like, I never figured it out.
You'll see, it was one of the first major teams.
Yeah, outside of your classical engineering.
Yeah, right.
And it was, you know, thriving.
That's right.
That's right.
And the urban need, you see, was there.
And then the deal fell off.
And it was very difficult to figure out what to do with it.
And then it went into strategic technology.

But the Center for Strategic Technology has evolved primarily into the strategic military-related technology, political technologies of the world, not the strategic sewer and prime and urban planning technology of cities.
which the business people really have a talent for doing.

They can draw in an interdisciplinary way the civil engineers and sanitary engineers, environmental engineers, those kinds of impacts that studies of strategic technologies of the urban community or the industrial development might need.
So those have merged now?
Those are all merged and that focus of the search happens in
the business technology.
How have different state, national, or international events affected communities in terms of massive amounts of funding, cutbacks in funding, particular types of programs?
Oh, that's ongoing all the time.
Constantly.
And
It's because that you have to realize that that's always there, particularly in the research business.
Above all other businesses, the research, whatever you want to call it, business, game, process, research is by its own nature very dynamic.
Yet when you...
Its value to society is measured by society in different ways.
And the ability to do it is determined by society's overall quality.
The first thing that disappears in a hard time
human nature.
The first thing that you do away with in your personal life when you have to go into a budget squeeze for whatever reason caused it, is what you would otherwise define as the luxury zone.
You may defer buying a new car, drive the old, long car, whatever.
Research is the feedback, really.
in the productivity cycle.
That is, it lives off of the profits of society.
You can model all of the whole world as just an industry.
If it doesn't have the leisure time, if it hasn't managed itself in a productive way, then there just might not be time to think.
And hence how you're going to lose

But if an industry doesn't produce enough resources to pay through its manufacturing process and its sales and marketing, its production, you won't have any resources to create your research division.
And you don't do research in production.
So these economic cycles that you're referring to occur.
Some, from the philosophy, have a change of administration.
They don't like that kind of thing.
But they like this kind of thing.
Reagan comes in and we need more defense, so the DOD's budget comes in.
